The government wants to limit the torture of “witches”, has published a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common characteristics.
Rather, they belong to the older generation, they cannot engage in work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
The one who becomes a witch is sent to isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is seldom reached."
“Young healthy women are not being expelled because they help with work and give birth to children,” describes a nun who takes care of more than a hundred women in a special house in Burkina Faso, the capital of the West African state, who have been expelled by their community.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She has published an information brochure that should help limit the witch hunt.
But there's a catch.
“More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” Die Standard reported.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Burkina Faso, Ghana, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after three women and two men tortured her, poured kerosene and set her on fire.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators claim that it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman was inflamed with oil, which is used for ritual anointing.
He said the group wanted to “put the demon out of the woman.”
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of their level of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The devouring of human souls has always been a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso, the witch hunt is being moderated by the government, in Gambia, the president himself participated last year.
"After the death of his aunt, the Gambian president Jammie launched a large-scale witch hunt, allegedly to take part in her death and try to use black magic to kill the president himself."
"He called for help from shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the President's personal protection, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from the Gambian villages to the President's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, the imprisoned people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which in addition caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly 1,000 prisoners were eventually released.
