There is also a kindergarten, the architects understand.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect to hide also a mini-school with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees can visit it.
Arch.Design, a design and architectural company whose studios were the basis of a number of important Brno buildings, counted on the space for its company mini-school from the very first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of the babyboomer, and it was important to her that women designers and architects could quickly return to work.
Along with the possibility of shortened hours, kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of a social program.
Thus, builders and architects have the opportunity to combine a demanding job with childcare.
The mini<0xC5><0xA1>kolka was invented by the Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The corporate mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidy of CZK 2.8 million), they could purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified personnel and operations for two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for a subsidy was significantly assisted by the company Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the nurse and the teacher of the Ministry of Education take care of the children all day long, so children without age restrictions can go to kindergarten, but most of them are over 3 years old.
Since it is a "miniskolka", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more will be replaced during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although this is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic cognition to preparation for school benches, the English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed picking up of children from kindergartens away from the parents' workplace are eliminated.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship.
Arch.Design has thus become one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look inside the interiors by Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Due to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all are typical of the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The facade of the house plays out dream lines, gentle colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
With detailed observation, you can see geometry, rhythm and a well-thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is further enhanced.
The twisting and twisting of shapes occurs equally in interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of the door, hoods and railings.
The Batll<0xC3><0xB3> House, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43, was rebuilt in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sal Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> himself.
It was designed by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his designer plank that decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
Many other artists and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>’s designs kicked off Jujola’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and Güell Park, which contains other works by Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname "House of Bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it a "going house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs include other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination may seem bizarre.
When creating Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> absolutely did not respect the then building regulations and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when the construction was completed, the city council was appalled and asked for repairs.
For example, the councillors were disturbed by the fact that the building was interfering with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, it was never repaired: only fifteen days after the challenge of the city district, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> requested (and successfully obtained) permission to lease the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a lounge and on the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewellery.
The whole six-storey house intersects the stairs, which can be climbed to the roof terrace itself.
The main elements of the reconstruction were the removal of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and a larger company can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, the house with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s reconstruction also received unconventional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>'s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which line the courtyard, and skylights is also impressive.
The play of two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is made available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the one hundred and fiftyth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed on the tours, as they found that it was a very advantageous business, and in addition they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you need to quickly make friends with one of the tenants of the apartment and visit it directly at home.
How to choose a mattress and a grid: women have different requirements than men
Not the grand frame of the bed, but the quality of the sleeping area, i.e. the mattress and the grid, give the basis for a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a specific user.
When choosing, many things are decided, from weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattresses and the grid are purchased.
Typical example?
For example, for weekend cottages, where they do not regularly warm up, latex mattresses are not suitable, because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
In this case, it is necessary to turn them regularly.
Because if they do not have a lot of vents in the core, and still lie on a hard board, they retain moisture: there could also be mold under them.
It is also customary to choose.
Who has spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, it will be difficult to feel good on a low and hard surface.
"Perhaps all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they wouldn't sleep here."
"They needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam on their battered shoulders, heels and hips."
“These are recommended for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder, so they misreceive ‘information’ from the joints and skin,” explains Sylva Hadamczik, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, but also other customers, were looking for a mattress with lazy foam years ago.
"Today it's cool, suitable mattresses have Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
Optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the absorbed heat or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing is pressing you, you will not turn over at night like after a hard game.
You'll just get a better night's sleep.
Lazy foam also acts as a protection against debris.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to your height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm therefore need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, such as singles, at least 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For comfort and a possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly bent in your elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, guildmaster of the Upholstery and Decorators Guild, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for many years and lectures it at vocational schools.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own grid and mattress, but here, be careful when buying to match the heights of the mattresses.
There is nothing else to do but to mount the grids to different heights, but this may not work for every frame of the bed.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring skeleton of at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on a molding and simmering layer.
"You must not feel the springs when you touch your hands or get on the mattress," warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grid.
Full-covered beds, where the mattresses and the base are like siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are poorly ventilated, it is impossible to wash their cover, which is already common today.
And since we usually sweat 0.2 to 0.75 liters per night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress begins to resemble a large (and clogged) sieve.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about the lifespan of mattresses up to 25 years, or even a lifetime warranty.
But everything has its ales.
That’s why the advice from retailers: do not give up the removable coating for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, but add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Even though mattress covers are commonly made around the circumference, so when unplugged, we get two parts (very important for washing and washing machine size!), however, manipulation in larger types (and in one person) when shooting could resemble a light weight duel in the ring with a heavy one.
Do you have a slab in your bed instead of a grid?
Never!
Maximum on the bed intended for one night visits.
However, the board should still be fitted with ventilation holes (if it no longer has them) and use a mattress with a spring skeleton and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (from it.Taschenfederkern) and a simmering layer.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a basis.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut) are suitable for non-positional lamella grills with 14 to 18 lamellas, but you always pay for grilles with more lamellas, 28 or more, where the lamellas are doubled in the thigh area and it is possible to regulate their stiffness.
The positioning lamellas do not include mattresses with spring skeleton, as they do not respond to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the slats, you can also indulge in the so-called shoulder cradle.
It is a special attachment of the slats, which allows you to push or even tilt the slat so that the shoulder of the sleeper is nicely "fallen".
For men who have "shoulder-to-shoulder" is definitely an important thing.
Even the manufacturers of mattresses remember it, who in the "men's" began to use the softening zone in the shoulder area.
They also remember women - they are given a softer surface in places of the hips.
For the most demanding customers are designed wing or plate grids with so-called multitorsion springs.
The pressure decomposes into multiple points and the voltage decreases.
However, beware, once you apply the wrong pillow (large and "swollen") to the right mattress and grid, most "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and only touch the shoulders with its tips so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size, 50 x 60 cm is recommended, which they prefer, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should balance the height of the shoulder (along with the shoulder cradle of the grid or the softened zone in the mattress).
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original straws filled with grasses.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is also in mattresses.
Raw materials from oil, from which polyurethane foams are made, are replaced by natural oils, for example, from skimpy and soybeans.
Soybeans are used by all well-known producers.
"Bio at the mattress means that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin," explains Petr V<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress coatings, one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also allow microcapsules to release the fresh smell of wood or lavender.
There is also a division between men and women.
While men are "cooled" by the plant extract from birch to allow the mattress cover to absorb heat and cool the body, women, on the contrary, "warm" the covers.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making the weaker sex warmer.
Today's favorites?
A mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with broken cellular structure, is thus more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
Combining the different stiffnesses of cold foams and "lazy" foams, multi-zone mattresses are created that know exactly where the head, thighs and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those that meet the health parameters, have a lower VAT rate, are taken as health aids.
In the Czech Republic, Gumotex was the first to achieve this advantage.
Saving on a mattress and a grid is not easy.
Sometimes you can use the events of manufacturers or sellers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with Memory foam sewn into the cover for CZK 11,990.
The second one can be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cellular structure and high density was started by the Tempur material at a "cosmic" rate.
It was originally created as a material for NASA, because during the launches, the astronauts were exposed to enormous overload.
Tempur softens in the heat, but in the cold it strengthens.
It adapts perfectly to the warm human body and optimally distributes its pressure.
It is therefore ideal against the formation of deformities, but also for increasing sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for medical products, such as special pillows under the feet, which relieve the legs and venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C foam or Twinsaver foam and the like.
