“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other endangering factors such as family health burdens, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants had an index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They had the same chance of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those who had the index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, while for men under 60, it was even a decrease of 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that promotes growing prostate cancer.
