The promotion of democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private enterprise.
Criminal activity is more worrying than unemployment.
And Brazil considers many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, is dominated by two related things.
The first is that Latin America has a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% annually since 2002, democracy support has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy recovered after a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are Democrats, drawing the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in their country, the same number as last year, but a large increase compared to 2001, when it was 25% (Figure 3).
Roughly 34% said they trust parliament in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, democracy in Latin America was undermined by the economic crisis.
Support arose during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
However, the mood varies across a wide range from ground to ground (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and the state of violent crime worsened.
For the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Roughly 31% say that either they themselves or their close relatives became victims of crime last year, but this is a decrease compared to 38% last year and also the lowest number since 1995.
More robust economic performance is reflected in growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage rose from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same view (and 80% support private business), although their left-wing president Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the region, as 19% of respondents mentioned (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to last year unchanged) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential respondent country in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
