Microbes with resistance to arsenic increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the scope for finding new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth and claim it is a sign that life has options that stand outside the main elements that have been considered so far and basic.
"This organism has a double ability."
"It can grow either through phosphorus or arsenic."
"This is a very strange fact, but it is not proof that it is some form of truly 'alien' life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of Science magazine.
For a long time, it was considered necessary for the life of six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after arsenic is replaced by phosphorus.
"You'll be amazed at what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is significant in the search for life beyond Earth, as researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report about this novelty published to be discussed, which did not disclose the details of the finding, has prompted widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to exploit other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the substitution of one element by another element in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't an accidental finding.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that the microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms are very difficult to separate these elements from one another."
"However, arsenic is so different that it does not work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it begins to work in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but because they can also survive with arsenic replacement, there is an increased possibility that a life form that uses arsenic may appear naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example of this.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it might have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
