Prosecutors won't blame Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Justice Department cleared Senator John Ensign of criminal charges relating to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure the lobby, the senator's lawyers said on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat that Mr Ensign, a Nevada Republican, faced and who was, until the scandal, considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012. His affair got into the national headlines and damaged his career.
Mr Ensign’s office said he was “delighted” by the decision, which followed almost a year of investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action at the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department "informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the target of the investigation and that there is no plan to bring further charges against him in this matter."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who argued that there was substantial evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing a violation of the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents published in the New York Times in October 2009 stated that Mr. Ensign was helping Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobby that was supposed to lead to Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, being silent about the senator’s relationship with her.
Mrs. Hampton used to work as a treasurer in the Ensign campaign.
Mr Ensign has contacted a number of political supporters to find work for Mr Hampton and to support their views after they have hired Mr Hampton to lobby for them, as documents and interviews say.
Since Hampton had been Mr. Ensign's assistant until recently, he was excluded from lobbying by law from his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts say the unusual settlement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to contradict the ban on lobbying.
From the evidence that was published, “it turned out that this is a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients who are being investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department was cautious about political lawsuits after a large number of setbacks, including last year’s decision to suspend the lawsuit against former Senator Ted Stevens amid charges of state misconduct.
Federal prosecutors “clearly concealed the weapons,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a legal group that filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign.
“This basically indicates that high-ranking government officials are not subject to the law,” she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr Ensign’s chief lawyer, said in an interview that he had been called by the Attorney General of the Department of Justice on Monday and then the next day, and had been told that the Department had found no charges against his client.
Mr Ensign's defense team is working with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had handed over to the public prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable describing the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice except that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to stop investigating a separate complaint in which an ethical group alleges that Ensign’s parents’ payment of $96,000 to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money meant nothing but a gift.
One company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find a lobbying job was NV Energy, a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator.
One email from December 2008 showed that after Mr. Hampton began to work as a lobbyist in the company, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, communicated with Mr. Hampton and told him that he had "blown" the Department of the Interior on the subject under discussion.
Mr Ensign also attended lunch with Mr Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and invited the Minister of Transport to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after they had hired Mr Hampton to work as a lobbyist.
When the scandal was first reported last year, Mr Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth Republican in the Senate.
After months of stagnation, Mr Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
In a report that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of the crime investigation, his spokesman Jennifer Cooper said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department and end the entire investigation.
“Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing her hard work on behalf of the Nevadan people,” she said.
