After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is already greater optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of the new opening treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on fundamental issues will not necessarily lead to a two-party relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, it is a likely period of disagreement, or even inevitable, he said.
"After the things that need to be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism - which is largely widespread - that politeness will lead to real cooperation.
“I look at everything between now and 2012 as a shadow boxing game when the main events take place in 2012,” he said.
The reasons are largely due to the formation of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea parties voters who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, knowing that they must act on their promises and must cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These support lines are clear in the initial responses to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Joint presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their view, to exert pressure on the deficit issue to public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to present their plan as an official recommendation and fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The biggest opposition is among the elected officials in the jury, who suggest that, in the case of financial issues, at least today, we have little basis or will to compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and the Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of party conflicts, with Republicans calling on Obama to address the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater party co-operation.
What causes the shift?
Public opinion.
There is a lot of evidence that, despite being partisan in the last election, most Americans still want to see two parties working together.
If it could go to the heel, as it did in 1995, then both sides will be watching the public’s reactions very closely.
Anyone who is threatened with a vote cut is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
