"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as the “slaughterer” for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander in this remote Khmer Rouge state in northwestern Cambodia remains popular, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is also broken in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims at the Truth and Reconciliation Forum were allowed to publicly confront people who were part of the regime.
In June, the government provided textbooks explaining for the first time the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers to children.
And in July, the United Nations and the Cambodian Court jointly upheld the first conviction of a former member of the Khmer Rouge, the verdict of the former leader, the notorious violent association Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the Spirit, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advance, there was growing unrest among Red Khmer veterans in Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to rejoin Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of the Cambodian Documentation Centre, an independent organization that is investigating the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was wonderful, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge regime in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government of Pol Pot in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its troops fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to the first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Red Khmer fighters began to move to the government, which culminated in the surrender of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who persisted, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters fell into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the time of the movement.
Although several elite Khmer Rouge have maintained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak, like unskilled farmers.
“These people have benefited from capitulation only minimally,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Vengu.
"They are surrounded by the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were raised with no idea of doing business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"The Mok fed them all."
"But now life is hard, because we have to take care of everything ourselves."
