“I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit.”
“This proves that the process is working,” said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for Global Security, a nuclear security group.
Clinton called the deal a “very important, important step” from Belarus.
Obama promised in Prague in April 2009 that he would secure all sensitive nuclear materials around the world within four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all of their reserves of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be 7th.
A dozen countries have done so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the Obama summit on nuclear safety, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko announced that his nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the basis for a weapon and less enriched uranium," Lukashenko said.
“It’s our commodity... We’re not going to make dirty bombs and we’re not going to sell them to anyone.”
"We only use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus a few months ago joined the United States and expressed interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to remove Belarusian uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was lightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded on a special train that travelled more than 1,300 miles to a Russian storage and disposal facility, officials said.
The second operation was closed on Monday and was carried out by air, officials said.
The U.S. government has spent $13 million on the program, most of it to supply the Belarusian research institute with less enriched uranium, which is not suitable for the production of nuclear weapons.
“Everything was coordinated very carefully and managed on a trust basis,” said Andrew Bieniawski, an energy ministry official working for Global Threat Reduction.
The James Martin Center for Non-Proliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of uranium for weapons production.
According to the joint statement, Belarus will seek to eliminate its reserves by 2012.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of Lukashenko’s cruel repression of human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggests the possibility of a gradual meltdown.
"We welcome progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus have recognized that more consistent respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains the basis for improving mutual relations and is essential for the progress of the country and its people," he said.
