Red Bull triumphs in Formula 1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The software proposes improvements in vehicles in real time.
Ever since Red Bull entered Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been characterized by surprise and success.
At first, no one took the possibilities of this newly incoming team very seriously, and despite the upward trend of recent times, everyone was betting on the triumph of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without wanting to reduce the equestrian abilities of the champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, or the capabilities of the Renault engine that drives his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - the "secret weapon" that multinational Siemens placed in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful software simulating the marches, which the German company launched in 2007 for purposes very distant to the automotive sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, has been used to design assembly lines in production plants around the world, in power plants, and for high-precision devices.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary mistakes and expenses.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains that the use of this software instrument allowed the Red Bull team to make “within a few hours, in near-real-time” modifications and improvements that would otherwise be detected during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in one period.
Today, the Red Bull team employs 180 young, highly skilled professionals equipped with powerful information technology to analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all components of Red Bull racing vehicles, except for the engine for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are being modified.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using lasers and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical achievement is the amount of $40 million, which is the maximum that any Formula 1 team can spend for each period to improve their competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a state-of-the-art technology plant about 50 km from London to design and manufacture its race cars.
These are two buildings that are restricted to visitors - especially journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered a "great secret".
The list of participants of this project includes 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull is without a doubt the new champion Sebastian Vettel.
However, behind the immeasurable technological means that the brand of energy drinks has put into its participation in racing circuits, there are other protagonists, whose help is invaluable, and yet no one knows them.
Chief Technology Officer Steve Nevey said that five years ago it was possible to say that advances in vehicle research and development contributed to the victory of 50% and the rest was due to the drivers.
Currently, this ratio has changed and the technology is worth the success of 85%, while pilots contribute 15%.
