Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but laid down conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, ranging from tax cuts for small and medium-sized enterprises, to the regulation of private intermediation agencies or the abolition of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>426 for the unemployed without benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA (Spanish Airports and Air Traffic Management - note.), the administrator of the airports Barajas and El Prae 30%
Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, on the other hand, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility to unleash the current crisis.
How to interpret these movements?
It should be said in advance that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, this is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which hints at the idea of adhering to old traditions, which is held by a large part of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, of which Germany would be a part, but also Austria and the Netherlands, for example, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the brand - although it may now seem like scifi, this version has wide public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to German proposals, is to revise the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budgetary rigour, fines for the guilty states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and with the extension of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is now no room for dials.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission spurred deficits in 2009, the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany considered correct (plans for fiscal rigor and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The other was shown by the Central European country, when Merkel painfully extended the decision to save Greece.
Already at that time it was the subject of harsh criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel reappeared with a clear position when she demanded that the European Union's conventions be reformed so as to allow the rescue of a Member State and at the same time that private creditors have a duty to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat relaxed form, has been approved, and we should be following the Union's reform process over the coming months, which should allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures must now be taken with which it seems to disagree too much, the old functioning of the euro will cease from that date.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which violators will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to report deferred payments, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany suggests to us that we must take a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
They simply do not want to tolerate another debt-based and building option, with huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed during Spain’s boom years.
The offer is clear.
And we would make a mistake if we didn't understand.
This is not just a recovery of the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much tougher.
And the worst thing is that under these conditions, we could happen to be wrong ourselves.
I hope that these current turbulences will be replaced by more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunity they give us by spring 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero also seems to have understood this, and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big businesses and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that despite criticism of Merkel, the road has opened to the idea that things need to be put in order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it does not seem to want to move it.
And of the options that can be considered, leaving the eurozone full of not-so-serious countries cannot be excluded.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that it warned us.
Sport and circumvention of rules
The fins shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax show wit not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behavior, and whether UEFA should eventually punish both players.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team clearly won) the named players were deliberately wasting time one by one when the foul was supposed to be played to provoke the referee, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will comply with the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in their group at the head - and will be able, stripped of their cards, to proceed to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Commission awarded coach José Mourinho a two-game penalty and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. rules that are unwritten, but follow each other.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that the Real Madrid team (which boasts in its anthem of generosity and honor, and which has already fined its players for similar actions) was a participant in it, and, as it seems, also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether circumvention of the law occurs in these acts; it is indeed an action respecting sports rules, the meaning of which, however, seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is decided what kind of damage such actions cause to the sports spirit.
One of the essentials of sports behavior is the physical integrity of the opponents, which in these cases was not violated, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these features that characterize clean play is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which also did not happen here.
Paradoxical to the action of the Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as deception or circumvention of the law did not happen, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should be as obvious as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
Another question, however, is what advantage will be given to the guilty of their wilful transgression.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that he will not achieve any benefit in the current match, since the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next stage of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance the team can be eliminated, and besides, players will be relieved of their punishment by this action, and move to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to exclude.
So how the rounds will continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid the punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention of rules is not clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly wit.
It seems to me that polemics arise for two reasons: because they were two self-exclusions, and because of the way in which instructions were transmitted to provoke them from the leadership.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
