U.S. to change visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Application Services before interviewing the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be shortened.
The visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change as of January 10, 2011.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Application Services Centres (abbreviated from English ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will remove the applicant’s biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging the meeting, the second for processing the application and others for delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only a single fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for tourist visas, $150 for visa applications (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visas will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and fingerprints will be taken from them.
As biometric information will be taken away in the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview meeting at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
