The World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
In Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n, the United Nations proposed a plan to restore domestic lighting, lighting of shops and industrial premises in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse effect (GES) limit, which corresponds to almost one-third of the additional limit that needs to be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push forward in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the lack of hard-to-realize commitments to reduce on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace incandescent bulbs, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, with fluo-compact bulbs or, even better, with bulbs with electroluminescence diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a significant amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated by lighting would be cut off.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70% of the world’s car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with a significant share of emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary plans to reduce global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance in order to achieve a stabilization of climate warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to exclude that it will not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluo-compact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, such as those introduced this week to the production of Philips - this company allegedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a glowing bulb, giving us an idea of a possible savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All of these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless producers set up collection centres.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact bulb, but rather a thermal coal-fired power plant, which releases a lot of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these centers release 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also details the gains that each country would make from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars a year to buy electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of a 3.5-billion-dollar thermal power plant.
