That's Dan Brown's mechanism of success.
The same goes for secret documents.
The informant is a lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) head of the secret services (and if he is not, he could, as I know, be an editor in the newspaper Libération) who considers only what he himself admits to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy to the State Department was the same that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why is there so much concern about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and since the heads of state can make phone calls or fly away by plane for a joint dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer watching films about the investigation knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that this seems to be ignored.
However, the fact that this is being repeated publicly defames the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most strictly classified information of the most powerful country in the world is a hard blow, not a negligible one, to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victim and his "executor".
But let's move on from here to the deep truth about what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's day, it was possible to conceive of all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orwell's prophecy has been proven since, thanks to the ability to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, the citizen became a total victim of the wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it is now, that even the "coffins" with the most secret information of the powerful can not resist the intervention of a hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker - elected as a citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can one maintain a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that the true secret is a meaningless secret (and a meaningless secret will never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious meaningless secret because it is drawn from public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, the secret of Hillary, the secret of all
WikiLeaks made no mistake with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to the bestowed power so significant?
It is obvious that in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would be equal to its publication on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is also quite obvious that with current technologies, it is useless to hope that you can keep a secret message over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state travelled by plane and made contact with one of his colleagues.
