Climate: how France hacked its funding pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test the compliance with the promises for quickly unlocked funding (speaked funding with a fast start or early start), implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been uncovered
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion for three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (that’s 420 million a year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to funding a fast start: a report clarifying the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations are invaluable and valued for their true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to deliver on its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion pledge in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is realised without compromising Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even be reduced), it is to comply with its commitment to finance "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, think that 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> borrowed is equal to 1<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> donated.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be evidenced for some investments that are profitable (often these are projects associated with reducing emissions, consisting in more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as the equivalent of our obligations, but as the cost of a loan to a lender country.
But France can only provide this justification: it is "compliant" with its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million commitment, which makes up 91.5% of the loan (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>388.8 million) and 8.5% of the donations (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the European Union that makes use of a loan on such a scale.
Germany claimed 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) kept their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, if the absolute majority of the European Union gives <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfill its promise, France will give only 10 centimes and considers this effort to be comparable.
What a beautiful piece of cake!
To sum up, in its financing of the “fast start” France operates with double deception: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time, and on the other hand, with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, it is able to convince that it spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million “new and additional” in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when only lending is enough?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is only a small issue, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
France should first announce a change in its way of keeping records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions on long-term financing deposits (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are recorded.
France should change its position to become as progressive with these deposits as with the others.
Therefore, everyone puts hope in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will come to Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could raise the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
An alarm about pesticides that children ingest.
A 10-year-old child consumes 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published this Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex-The Movement for Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results "have no significant statistical value given the low number of analysed samples but are characteristic of the issues being processed," bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack per child about a decade old in supermarkets in Paris.
These typical foods, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as confectionery, were analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are considered carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are among the clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to internally exfoliated glands (PE), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
“Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we can well see that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, perhaps carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain in themselves about ten residuums with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya included in the lunch, for which studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna, and even bread and chewing gum were spiked with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analysis revealed the presence of nitrate and chloroform.
Salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even an analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave did not escape analysis.
“The ultimate risk to consumers of this ‘contaminant cocktail’ is likely to be underestimated,” the study said.
The Ecological Europe-Greens Association (EE-LV) has proposed "face-to-face emergency" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the "increase in civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
